				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varepsilon_{d} = \varepsilon_{L} + \chi^{(3)} \left| E \right|^{2}$$\end{document}where εL is the linear dielectric constant, which is adjusted at 2.25, χ(3) denotes the third-order nonlinear susceptibility which reads 4 × 10–18 m2/V2, and |E|2 is the intensity of the incident light that changes the InGaAsP properties.

With our chosen angle (θ = 45°), the transmission spectrum of the slanted stub length variation (d) has been shown in Fig. 5a. According to the figure, by increasing d, a clear red shift of the first resonance mode wavelength occurred. According to the scattering matrix method, the excited SPP wavelength in a single stub can be described as (Yang et al. 2018):2λm=4dneff2m+1-Δφπ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
