				\begin{document}$${\uplambda }_{m} = \frac{{4dn_{eff} }}{{\left( {2m + 1} \right) - \frac{\Delta \varphi }{\pi }}}$$\end{document}where λm is the transmittance spectrum resonance wavelength, m is an integer number, Δφ is the phase shift generated from the reflection on the dielectric silver interface, d is the geometric parameters of a single stub, and neff is the effective refractive index of the structures' mediums. Therefore, the resonance wavelength is dependent on the stub geometry dimensions and the interference between traveling waves. As a result, multiple resonances result from the destructive interference between the slanted stub resonator with long length (d) and the bus waveguide waves. These promising outcomes may pave the way for shifting the wavelength of the notch filter and adding additional trapped wavelengths to work as a multiple-notch filter. Based on the previous inspection, a relationship between the first “trapped” resonance wavelength and the length of the slanted stub resonators has been illustrated in Fig. 5b. We can formulate this relationship by using the MATLAB curve fitting tool as follow:3λ=2.7d+170\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
