				\begin{document}$$\lambda = 2.7d + 170$$\end{document}where λ and d are in (nm). As reported by Eq. (3), a notch filter can be simply designed with a desired resonance “trapped” wavelength to be worked in visible light communication systems (Vitasek et al. 2016) and as an RGB filter a in CCD camera (Kaplan et al. 2011). Also, by increasing stub length, a multiple-notch wavelength filter can be obtained. Figure 5c, d, e, illustrate the magnitude of the electric field distribution for the “Trapped” and Passed wavelengths of the proposed static PNF with stub resonator rotation angle θ = 45° and length d = 300 nm.Fig. 5
a Transmission spectrum of a single slanted stub resonator filter with different lengths, b Relationship between first resonance mode “Trapped” wavelengths with stub length variation, c Electrical field pattern at λ = 520 nm with d = 300 nm, d Electrical field pattern at λ = 980 nm with d = 300 nm, e Electrical field pattern at λ = 800 nm with d = 300 nm, the stub angle and width are fixed at 45°, 50 nm, respectively

To establish a tunable filter with a large tunability range, the incident light intensity, which was exposed to the InGaAsP medium, must be greater than 1 × 1016 v2/m2, since when the incident light intensity is less than 1 × 1016 v2/m2, no shifting in the notch wavelength happens, see Fig. 6a. As illustrated in Fig. 6b, by increasing the incident light intensity, the notch wavelength is shifted to longer wavelength bands with a dynamic tunability range of 200 nm, which covers the visible and near IR spectrums. All the notch wavelengths (λ = 840, 900, 980, 1040 nm) are filtered out with equal bandwidth = 50 nm, which means there is no crosstalk between them. The relation between the light intensity exposed to the InGaAsP dielectric material and the notch wavelength has been clarified through Fig. 7. It is clear from the figure that there is a direct positive relationship between filtering wavelengths and light intensity exposed to the nonlinear InGaAsP material. The electric field distribution of the four notch wavelengths corresponding to four different light intensities has been listed in Table 3. From that table, it can be observed that depending on the amount of light that is exposed to the InGaAsP material, a certain notch wavelength has been trapped in the slanted stub with no interference between wavelengths. As a result, by varying the intensity of the incident light, this plasmonic filter can be utilized as an optical switch to optically switch between two different wavelengths. For example, we can optically switch between λ = 840, and λ = 900 by changing the laser pumping state from OFF to ON state with intensity = 10 × 1016 v2/m2. Figure 8 displays the attenuation curve for various waveguide configurations. With no slanted stub configuration, all wavelengths pass through the waveguide with the same small attenuation. With a slanted “air dielectric” stub, a high attenuation was observed at the notch wavelength (λ = 580 nm). By filling "the air dielectric" with "InGaAsP medium", the attenuation curve has been shifted to higher wavelengths based on the intensity variation of the incident light beam.Fig. 6
